Myths about Keto I hear all the time. 

-Eating fats is not ketosis or burning ketones.

For many people, keto-adapted means ketosis, but it doesn't not.

Just eating fats and protein doesn't mean keto, and it sure as heck doesn't mean keto-adapted. 

When you start eating high fats with very low carbs and moderate to low protein, your body will search for resources.  Your liver will begin to kick out some ketones to keep the brain and muscles fed.

Depending on the inflammation, genetics, and disease state of the person doing the keto diet, it can take anywhere from 2 to 12 weeks to become adapted. 

Adaption is where the magic happens. Rarely does anyone make adaption because they take too many carbs refeeds in the beginning, or they cheat too much, or they take medications or stimulants that raise glucose levels and kick them out of ketosis. 

True adaption is how disease can end, but it's much harder for many people than you think.
